{{distinguish|Golden calf}} [[Image:Chrysobull of Alexius III of Trebizond.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Imperial chrysobull of [[Alexios III of Trebizond]], 1374]] [[Image:Goldene-bulle 1c-480x475.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The [[Golden Bull of 1356]] issued by Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV]] [[File:Zlatna bula Bele IV.gif|right|thumb|200px|The [[Golden Bull of 1242]] by [[Béla IV of Hungary|Béla IV]] to inhabitants of [[Zagreb]] in [[Croatia]]]]
A '''golden bull''' or '''chrysobull''' was a [[decree]] issued by [[Byzantine Emperor]]s and later by monarchs in Europe during the [[Middle Ages]] and [[Renaissance]], most notably by the [[Holy Roman Emperors]]. The term was originally coined for the golden [[Seal (emblem)|seal]] (a ''[[Bulla (seal)|bulla]] aurea''), attached to the decree, but came to be applied to the entire decree. Such decrees were known as golden bulls in western Europe and ''chrysobullos logos'', or chrysobulls, in the Byzantine Empire (χρυσός, ''chrysos'', being [[Greek language|Greek]] for [[gold]]).
For nearly eight hundred years, they were issued unilaterally, without obligations on the part of the other party or parties. However, this eventually proved disadvantageous as the Byzantines sought to restrain the efforts of foreign powers to undermine the empire. During the 12th century, the Byzantines began to insert into golden bulls sworn statements of the obligations of their negotiating partners.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}
Notable golden bulls included:
* [[Byzantine–Venetian Treaty of 1082|The Golden Bull of 1082]], issued by [[Alexios I Komnenos]] to grant [[Venice]] merchants with free trading rights, exempt from tax, throughout the [[Byzantine Empire]] in return for their defense of the [[Adriatic Sea]] against the [[Normans]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Crowley|first=Roger|title=City of Fortune: How Venice Ruled the Seas|year=2012|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=978-1400068203}}</ref> * The Golden Bull of 1136, issued by [[Pope Innocent II]], more commonly known as the [[Bull of Gniezno]]. * The [[Golden Bull of Sicily]], issued in 1212 by [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor]]. * The [[Golden Bull of 1213 (German)|Golden Bull of 1213]], issued by [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor]]. * The [[Golden Bull of 1213 (English)|Golden Bull of 1213]], issued by the papacy to recognize its agreement with [[John Lackland]] (more commonly known as [[King John of England]]). * The [[Golden Bull of 1214]], issued by [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor]] to cede all German territories north of the rivers [[Elbe]] and [[Elde]] to King [[Valdemar II of Denmark|Valdemar the Victorious]] of [[Denmark]]. * The [[Golden Charter of Bern|Golden Bull of Berne]], supposedly issued by Frederick II in 1218, but now considered a forgery. * The [[Golden Bull of 1222]], issued by King [[Andrew II of Hungary]] to confirm the rights of nobility and forced on him in much the same way [[King John of England]] was made to sign the [[Magna Carta]]. * The [[Diploma Andreanum|Golden Bull of 1224]] (the ''Goldener Freibrief'') issued by Andrew to grant certain rights to the [[Saxon people|Saxon]] [[Transylvanian Saxons|inhabitants]] of [[Transylvania]]. * The [[Golden Bull of Rimini]] (1226), issued by [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor]]. * The [[Golden Bull of 1242]] issued by King [[Béla IV of Hungary|Béla IV]] to proclaim a [[Borough|free royal Borough]] (a free and royal city) for the inhabitants of [[Gradec, Zagreb|Gradec]] (today's [[Zagreb]]) and [[Samobor]] in [[Croatia]], during the [[Mongol invasion of Europe]].<ref>[http://mirror.veus.hr/stamps/1992/bula.html 750th Anniversary of the Golden Bull Granted by Bela IV] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050428125414/http://mirror.veus.hr/stamps/1992/bula.html |date=2005-04-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | language = Croatian | newspaper = [[Vjesnik]] | date = 1998-11-17 | author = M. Šašić | location = Zagreb | title = »Zlatna bula« - temelj razvoja Zagreba kroz stoljeća | url = http://www.vjesnik.hr/Html/1998/11/17/Zagreb.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090104180858/http://www.vjesnik.hr/Html/1998/11/17/Zagreb.htm | archivedate = 2009-01-04}}</ref> * The [[Golden Bull of 1267]], issued by King [[Bela IV of Hungary]]. * The [[Golden Bull of 1348]], issued by [[List of rulers of Bohemia|King]] [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles I]] of [[Bohemia]], later [[Holy Roman Emperor]] as Charles IV, to confer privileges and immunities on [[Charles University of Prague|Charles University]] established by [[Pope Clement VI]] in [[Prague]], [[List of oldest universities in continuous operation|one of the oldest universities in the world]]. * The [[Golden Bull of 1356]] (one of the most famous golden bulls), issued by [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV]] for promulgation at the [[Diet of Nuremberg]], to define (and to last more than four hundred years) the constitutional structure of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. * The [[Golden Bull of 1702]], issued by [[Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor]] to establish the ''Akademia Leopoldina'' in the [[Silesia]]n capital of [[Breslau]] (present name: [[Wrocław]]), the future [[University of Wrocław|University of Breslau]] (''Universitas Vratislatensis'').
