{{italic title}}
{{For|the canonical tribunal|Roman Rota}}

[[Image:Alexander III Rota.png|thumb|''Rota'' of [[Pope Alexander III]], AD&nbsp;1175]]
The '''''rota''''' is one of the symbols used by the [[Pope]] to authenticate documents such as [[papal bull]]s. It is a cross inscribed in two concentric circles. [[Pope Leo IX]] was the first pope to use it.

The four inner quadrants contain: "[[Saint Peter|''Petrus'']]", "[[Paul of Tarsus|''Paulus'']]", the Pope's name, and the Pope's ordinal number. The Pope's [[autograph]] or motto is sometimes inscribed between the concentric circles.

A ''rota'' was also used by monarchs for the authentication of documents and [[diploma|diplomas]].<ref>For instance, it was used by [[William I of Sicily]] and [[William II of Sicily]]: Antonia Gransden, ''Legends, Traditions, and History in Medieval England'', Continuum International Publishing Group, 1992, p. 184.</ref>

